0–1510":"1450–1510","1450–1509":"1450–1509","1465–1510":"1465–1510","1400–1443":"1400–1443","1400–Female":"1400–Afdød","29 November 1470":"29. november 1470","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1425":"1425","1535":"1535","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1443":"1443","1465":"1465","30 November 1470":"30. november 1470","1430":"1430","1509":"1509",", , Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Little Baddow, Essex, England":"Little Baddow, Essex, England","Essex, Hertfordshire, England":"Essex, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Little Baddow":"Baddow, Queensland, Australien"},"nl":{"1425–30 November 1470":"1425–30 november 1470","1425–1470":"1425–1470","1430–1535":"1430–1535","1425–Female":"1425–Overleden","1450–1510":"1450–1510","1450–1509":"1450–1509","1465–1510":"1465–1510","1400–1443":"1400–1443","1400–Female":"1400–Overleden","29 November 1470":"29 november 1470","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1425":"1425","1535":"1535","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1443":"1443","1465":"1465","30 November 1470":"30 november 1470","1430":"1430","1509":"1509",", , Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Little Baddow, Essex, England":"Little Baddow, Essex, England","Essex, Hertfordshire, England":"Essex, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Little Baddow":"Baddow, Queensland, Australië"},"en":{"1425–30 November 1470":"1425–30 November 1470","1425–1470":"1425–1470","1430–1535":"1430–1535","1425–Female":"1425–Deceased","1450–1510":"1450–1510","1450–1509":"1450–1509","1465–1510":"1465–1510","1400–1443":"1400–1443","1400–Female":"1400–Deceased","29 November 1470":"29 November 1470","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","1425":"1425","1535":"1535","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1443":"1443","1465":"1465","30 November 1470":"30 November 1470","1430":"1430","1509":"1509",", , Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Little Baddow, Essex, England":"Little Baddow, Essex, England","Essex, Hertfordshire, England":"Essex, England","Saint Mary the Virgin Little Baddow":"Baddow, Queensland, Australia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Toft","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Hjalmer, Nels, Thorval.","English (Lancashire, Cheshire and Staffordshire): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Cambridgeshire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Warwickshire, named with Middle English <i>toft(e)</i> (Old Norse <i>topt</i>, Old Danish <i>toft</i>), denoting a plot of land on which a house stands or formerly stood. The surname may also be topographic, for someone who lived by or on a toft.","Scandinavian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads or placenames derived from Old Norse <i>topt</i> ‘curtilage, site, homestead’."],"variants":[{"name":"Tufts","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of <b>Tofts</b>, itself a variant of   Toft   with plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Tift","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Toft  ."]},{"name":"Tuft","meanings":["English (Staffordshire): variant of   Toft  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads so named, from Old Norse <i>tupt</i> ‘site, lot’.","Possibly an altered form of South German <b>Duft</b>, a topographic name meaning ‘swamp, moor’."]},{"name":"Taft","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire and Derbyshire): variant of   Toft  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial or metonymic occupational name from German <i>Taft</i> ‘taffeta’.","History: Robert Taft (born <i>c.</i> 1640), lived in Braintree, MA, and subsequently Mendon, MA. — Alphonso Taft (1810–91), jurist and politician born in Townshend, VT, was the father of William Howard Taft (1857–1930), 27th president of the US and chief justice of the US Supreme Court."]},{"name":"Tofte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Hjalmer, Iver, Steinar, Thora.","Scandinavian (mainly Norwegian): variant of   Toft  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Toft was born in 1425, in Little Baddow, Essex, England, his father, Sir William Toft, was 25 and his mother, Idonea Toft, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Leventhorpe 15GGM. He died on 30 November 1470, in Essex, England, at the age of 45, and was buried in Baddow, Queensland, Australia."},"et":{"1425–30 November 1470":"1425–30. november 1470","1425–1470":"1425–1470","1430–1535":"1430–1535","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1450–1510":"1450–1510","1450–1509":"1450–1509","1465–1510":"1465–1510","1400–1443":"1400–1443","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","29 November 1470":"29. november 1470","1450"